article.description: Tyrone Sally scored 17 points and braved a bloody nose suffered in a second-half collision to lead West Virginia to a 65-54 win over Kent State in the opening round of the NIT on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Sally scores 17, survives bloody nose
article.linkText: Sally, Mountaineers climb past Kent State
article.story: KENT, Ohio (AP) -- Tyrone Sally scored 17 points and braved a bloody nose from a second-half collision to lead West Virginia to a 65-54 win over Kent State in the opening round of the NIT on Wednesday night. It was the first postseason win for the Mountaineers (16-13) since they reached the regional semifinals of the 1998 NCAA tournament. The Golden Flashes (22-9) lost six of their final eight games. Sally spent several minutes on the floor under his basket after colliding with Kent State center John Edwards with 9:14 remaining and the Mountaineers leading 46-41. The 6-foot-7 junior returned to the game two minutes later and West Virginia ahead 46-43. Sally scored only two points in the final 7:17, but his defense in the middle of a 1-3-1 zone helped force four turnovers down the stretch, when the Mountaineers outscored the Golden Flashes 19-11. The Mountaineers' zone perpetually frustrated Kent State shooters. The Golden Flashes shot just 32 percent from the field, including 4-for-27 on 3-pointers. Kent State finished its season by making just six of its last 44 3-pointers. Kent State senior Eric Haut, who made 40 percent of his 3s during the regular season, was just 1-of-10 behind the arc. Reserve Clif Brown scored 14 points in 18 minutes for Kent State after playing just three minutes in three MAC tournament games. Edwards added 13 points. Patrick Beilein scored 14 points and D'or Fischer added 12 for West Virginia. The Mountaineers advanced to play Rhode Island (20-13) in the first round. The winner of that game will advance to the second round against Rutgers (17-12).
